The paper deals with coding theory and information theory, which are both subfields of computer science. The use of sparse matrices in constructing universal codes suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-categories of information theory (cs.IT) and information theory and signal processing (cs.ITP). The paper also involves the use of hash property, which is a concept related to data structures and algorithms, suggesting that it may also belong to the sub-categories of data structures (cs.DS) and distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). Finally, the paper deals with channel coding, which is a subfield of communication theory, suggesting that it may also belong to the sub-category of computer communication (cs.CC).
